Lattice

library(lattice)
library(mlmRev)
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: lme4
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: Matrix

The following dataset records information on students appearing in the 1997 A-level chemistry examination in Britain:

df <- mlmRev::Chem97

head(df)

We are interested in the following variables:

  • score: point score in the exam, with 6 possible values (0, 2, 4, 6, 8)

-gcsescore: average score in GCSE exams (may be used as a predictor)

-gender

Let’s try to draw an histogram with Lattice:

histogram(~ gcsescore, data = df)

We would like to display the distribution of gcsescore compared across different subgroups, such as those defined by score

histogram(~ gcsescore | factor(score), data = df)

We could also subdivide the gcsescore values by gender:

densityplot(~ gcsescore | factor(score), df, groups = gender, plot.points = F, auto.key = T)

Available display types in lattice

  • histogram()

  • densityplot() : Kernel Density Plot

  • qqmath() : Theoretical Quantile Plot

qqmath(~ gcsescore | factor(score), df, groups = gender, f.value = ppoints(100), auto.key = T, type = c('p', 'g'), aspect = 'xy')

  • qq() : Two-sample Quantile Plot
qq(gender ~ gcsescore | factor(score), df, f.value = ppoints(100), type = c('p', 'g'), aspect = 1)

  • stripplot() : Stripchart (Comparative 1D Scatter plots)
stripplot(depth ~ factor(mag), data = quakes, jitter.data = T, alpha = 0.6, main = 'Depth of earthquake epicenter by magnitude', xlab = 'Magnitude (Richter)', ylab = 'Depth (km)')

  • bwplot() : Comparative Box-and-Whisker Plots
bwplot(factor(score) ~ gcsescore | gender, df)

bwplot(gcsescore ~ gender | factor(score), df, layout = c(6, 1))

  • barchart()
VADeathsDF <- as.data.frame.table(VADeaths, responseName = 'Rate')

VADeathsDF
barchart(Var1 ~ Rate | Var2, VADeathsDF, layout = c(4, 1))

We can set the origin to 0:

barchart(Var1 ~ Rate | Var2, VADeathsDF, layout = c(4, 1), origin = 0)

  • dotplot()
dotplot(Var1 ~ Rate | Var2, VADeathsDF, layout = c(4, 1))

We can use Var2 as a grouping variable:

dotplot(Var1 ~ Rate, data = VADeathsDF, groups = Var2, type = 'o', auto.key = list(space = 'right', points = T, lines = T))

The following one produces the same as before:

dotplot(VADeaths, type = 'o', auto.key = list(points = T, lines = T, space = 'right'))

Some Example

Italy is importing an item A from 5 other countries (US, UK, Russia, China, Brazil). In the last 300 months (Jan 1994 - Dec 2018), the imported QUANTITIES are:

set.seed(42)
from_us <- rnorm(300, 500, 50)
from_uk <- rnorm(300, 200, 20)
from_ru <- rnorm(300, 1000, 75)
from_cn <- rnorm(300, 800, 10)
from_br <- rnorm(300, 300, 40)

The import PRICE has changed throughout the years as follows:

set.seed(42)
price_from_us <- seq(from = 1.1, to = 2.5, length.out = 300)
price_from_uk <- seq(from = 1.5, to = 2.0, length.out = 300)
price_from_ru <- seq(from = 0.7, to = 2.0, length.out = 300)
price_from_cn <- seq(from = 0.2, to = 4.0, length.out = 300)
price_from_br <- seq(from = 0.5, to = 1.2, length.out = 300)

Let’s build a dataframe from this data:

imports <- data.frame(month = format(seq(as.Date("1994/01/01"), by = 'month', length.out = 300), "%m %Y"),
                      quantity = c(from_us, from_uk, from_ru, from_cn, from_br),
                      price = c(price_from_us, price_from_uk, price_from_ru, price_from_cn, price_from_br),
                      country = as.factor(c(rep('us', 300), rep('uk', 300), rep('ru', 300), rep('cn', 300), rep('br', 300))))

and add the total_cost column:

imports$total_cost <- imports$quantity * imports$price

let’s also see the range of the quantity:

range(imports$quantity)
## [1]  150.7733 1240.8399

let’s initialzie an xyplot() with x going from 0 to 300 (300 months) and y from 0 to 1300 (max quantity is 1240):

library(lattice)

xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300))

convert_dates <- function(month){
  return(format(as.Date(paste('01', month, sep = ' '), format = '%d %m %Y'), '%b %y'))
}

xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300),
       main = list(label = 'Import volume', cex = 1.5),                                          #Main title label and expansion factor
       xlab = list(label = 'Date', cex = 1.4),                                                   #Xlab label and expansion factor
       ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),                                        #Ylab label and expansion factor
       scales = list(x = list(at = c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50)),                                  #Set ticks for x : [1, 50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300]
                              label = convert_dates(imports$month[c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50))]), #To positions defined in at, we give labels converting months with previous function
                              rot = 45, cex = 1.2),                                              #Also we rotate by 45° and with expansion factor of 1.2
                     y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.2)))                          #Set ticks for y : [0, 250, 500, 750, 1000, 1250]

#Let's also plot the data

mycols <- c('red', 'blue', 'black', 'orange', 'yellow')
names(mycols) <- unique(imports$country)                #associate to each color a country name

xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300),
       main = list(label = 'Import volume', cex = 1.5),
       xlab = list(label = 'Date', cex = 1.4),
       ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),
       scales = list(
         x = list(at = c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50)),
             label = convert_dates(imports$month[c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50))]),
             rot = 45, cex = 1.2),
         y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.2)
         ),
       panel=function(...){                                                                                 #panel=function(...) structure plot in a lattice element
         for(i in unique(imports$country)){                                                                 #for all the 5 countries
           lpoints(1:300, imports$quantity[imports$country == i], type = 'p', pch = 19, col = mycols[i])    #plot a scatterplot, where x is a progression from 1 to 300 and y is equal to the quantity corresponding to that particular country
         }                                                                                                  #Also, with p we plot just points, pch=19 is the type of points to use, and color taken from mycols list, progressively
        }
       )

plot with lines:

xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300),
       main = list(label = 'Import volume', cex = 1.5),
       xlab = list(label = 'Date', cex = 1.4),

       ),
       panel=function(...){                                                                                 #panel=function(...) structure plot in a lattice element
         for(i in unique(imports$country)){                                                                 #for all the 5 countries
           lpoints(1:300, imports$quantity[imports$country == i], type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = mycols[i])    #plot a scatterplot, where x is a progression from 1 to 300 and y is equal to the quantity corresponding to that particular country
         }                                                                                                  #Also, with p we plot just points, pch=19 is the type of points to use, and color taken from mycols list, progressively
       }
)

Add a legend:

library(Hmisc)
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: survival
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: Formula
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: ggplot2
## 
## Caricamento pacchetto: 'Hmisc'
## I seguenti oggetti sono mascherati da 'package:base':
## 
##     format.pval, units
xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300),
       main = list(label = 'Import volume', cex = 1.5),
       xlab = list(label = 'Date', cex = 1.4),
       ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),
       scales = list(
         x = list(at = c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50)),
                  label = convert_dates(imports$month[c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50))]),
                  rot = 45, cex = 1.2),
         y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.2)
       ),
       key = list(x = 0.1, y = 0.1,                                                                         #pos of legend x, y
                  lines = list(lwd = 4, col = mycols[unique(imports$country)]),                             #prepares lines of lwd=4 in different colors
                  text = list(label = capitalize(as.character(unique(imports$country))), cex = 1.75),       #add country names near lines. Where names are transformed into characters and capitalized
                  padding.text = 4,                                                                         #add white space around the text 
                  border = T,                                                                               #add border around legend's box
                  columns = 5),                                                                             #split legend in 5 columns, one for each country, and one row
       panel=function(...){
         for(i in unique(imports$country)){
           lpoints(1:300, imports$quantity[imports$country == i], type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = mycols[i])
         }
       }
)

Now find month with maximal import, using sqldf package to interact with the DF as a database:

library(sqldf)
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: gsubfn
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: proto
## Caricamento del pacchetto richiesto: RSQLite
#total quantity for each month
summarised <- sqldf('select month, sum(quantity) as total_quantity from imports group by month') #SQL query to data

mx <- which(summarised$total_quantity == max(summarised$total_quantity), arr.ind = T)            #and find which date is == max of total_quality


#now we add this piece of information to the plot:

xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300),
       main = list(label = 'Import volume', cex = 1.5),
       xlab = list(label = 'Date', cex = 1.4),
       ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),
       scales = list(
         x = list(at = c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50)),
                  label = convert_dates(imports$month[c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50))]),
                  rot = 45, cex = 1.2),
         y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.2)
       ),
       key = list(x = 0.1, y = 0.1,
                  lines = list(lwd = 4, col = mycols[unique(imports$country)]),
                  text = list(label = capitalize(as.character(unique(imports$country))), cex = 1.75),
                  padding.text = 4,
                  border = T,
                  columns = 5),
       panel=function(...){
         for(i in unique(imports$country)){
           lpoints(1:300, imports$quantity[imports$country == i], type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = mycols[i])
         }
         lsegments(x0 = mx, y0 = 100, x1 = mx, y1 = 1250, col = 'green', lwd = 3)                                       #segment of which x0 is mx and goes in y from 100 to 1250
         ltext(mx, 1280, col = 'green', label = paste('Max import on', convert_dates(imports$month[mx]), sep = ' '),    #add text with x coord mx and y coord 1280 (just above the end of the segment), with text: 'Max import on' given date
                 cex = 1.4)
       }
)

Let’s move on a boxplot

bwplot(quantity ~ country, data = imports)

Polish it:

bwplot(imports$quantity ~ imports$country,
       par.settings = list(box.umbrella = list(lty = 1)),
       main = list(label = 'Import distribution', cex = 1.5),
       xlab = list(label = 'Country', cex = 1.4),
       ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),
       scales = list(
         y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.3),
         x = list(label = capitalize(as.character(sort(unique(imports$country)))), cex = 1.3)
         ),
         panel  = function(...){
           panel.bwplot(notch = F, ...)                                                                                                                                                                               #bwplot, notch = F to not stack together
           for (i in 1:5){                                                                                                                                                                                            #for each country:
             panel.points(x = jitter(rep(i, 300), amount = .5), imports[imports$country==sort(unique(imports$country))[i], 'quantity'], col = mycols[sort(unique(imports$country))[i]], pch = 19, alpha = 0.5)        #we draw points on the panel, jittering them and take from imports only the quantity column. Finally set colors through mycols vector
           }
         }
       )

Let’s put together xyplot() and bwplot():

g1 <- xyplot(c(0, 1300) ~ c(1, 300),
             main = list(label = 'Import volume', cex = 1.5),
             xlab = list(label = 'Date', cex = 1.4),
             ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),
             scales = list(
               x = list(at=c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50)), label = convert_dates(imports$month[c(1, seq(50, 300, by = 50))]), rot = 45, cex = 1.2),
               y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.2)
             ),
             key = list(x = 0.1, y = 0.1,
                        lines = list(lwd = 4, col = mycols[unique(imports$country)]),
                        text = list(label = capitalize(as.character(unique(imports$country))), cex = 1.75),
                        padding.text = 4,
                        border = T,
                        columns = 3),
             panel = function(...){
               for (i in unique(imports$country)){
                 lpoints(1:300, imports$quantity[imports$country==i], type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = mycols[i])
               }
               lsegments(x0 = mx, y0 = 100, x1 = mx, y1 = 1250, col = 'green', lwd = 3)
               ltext(mx, 1280, col = 'green', label = paste('Max import on', convert_dates(imports$month[mx]), sep = ' '),
                     cex = 1.4)
               }
             )

g2 <- bwplot(imports$quantity ~ imports$country, par.settings = list(box.umbrella = list(lty = 1)),
             main = list(label = 'Import distribution', cex = 1.5),
             xlab = list(label = 'Country', cex = 1.4),
             ylab = list(label = 'Quantity (tons)', cex = 1.4),
             scales = list(
               y = list(at = seq(0, 1300, by = 250), cex = 1.3),
               x = list(label = capitalize(as.character(sort(unique(imports$country)))), cex = 1.3)
             ),
             panel = function(...){
               panel.bwplot(notch=T,...)
               for (i in 1:5){
                 panel.points(x = jitter(rep(i, 300), amount = 0.5), imports[imports$country == sort(unique(imports$country))[i], 'quantity'], col = mycols[sort(unique(imports$country))[i]], pch = 19, alpha = 0.5)
               }
             }
)
